The paper deals with regular languages and finite semigroups, which are topics typically studied in the formal language theory (cs.FL) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The use of compressibility measures to classify the intersection problem into circuit complexity classes suggests a connection to computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The mention of structural and non-structural properties determining the complexity of the problem suggests a connection to logic and set theory (cs.LO). Finally, the mention of decidability in quasi-polynomial time suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT).
